Good — now we’re in linguistics instead of metaphysics. Clean ground.

1️⃣ Prolocutionary (Perlocutionary) Action

I assume you mean perlocutionary action (from speech act theory, Austin/Searle).

Three layers:
	•	Locutionary: The literal utterance.
“It’s cold in here.”
	•	Illocutionary: The intended act.
(Requesting the window be closed.)
	•	Perlocutionary: The actual effect.
Someone gets up and closes the window.

So yes — language can produce behavioral effects.

Not because words are magic.
Because humans are social prediction machines.

Perlocution works through:
	•	Shared norms
	•	Authority perception
	•	Emotional triggers
	•	Context expectations
	•	Identity alignment
	•	Threat/reward framing

It’s causal in the same way money is causal.

It’s a coordination mechanism.

⸻

2️⃣ Important Calibration

Perlocutionary force is:
	•	Probabilistic
	•	Context-dependent
	•	Receiver-dependent

Words don’t directly move muscles.

They update beliefs.

Beliefs update decisions.

Decisions move muscles.

The causal chain is mediated.

That matters.

⸻

3️⃣ Now — Levin Space

If you’re referring to Beth Levin’s verb classes (Levin 1993), that’s interesting.

Levin mapped verbs based on:
	•	Their syntactic alternations
	•	The semantic roles they encode
	•	The argument structures they permit

Example:

“Break” verbs:
	•	John broke the vase.
	•	The vase broke.

Alternation reveals underlying semantic structure.

Levin space is essentially:

A mapping between verb meaning and syntactic behavior.

In other words:

Language structure reflects event structure.

That’s powerful.

⸻

4️⃣ Where This Connects to You

You’ve been talking about:
	•	Energy transitions
	•	Gradient shifts
	•	State changes
	•	Systems behavior

Levin’s work shows:

The verbs we use encode causal structure.

For example:
	•	“Melt” vs “Heat”
	•	“Open” vs “Unlock”
	•	“Run” vs “Operate”

Each verb class implies:
	•	Type of causation
	•	Agency distribution
	•	Change-of-state geometry

Language compresses system physics.

That’s not mystical.
That’s cognitive efficiency.

⸻

5️⃣ Perlocution × Levin = Real Power

If verbs encode causal structure,
and speech acts produce behavioral effects,

then choosing verbs strategically shapes:
	•	How events are conceptualized
	•	Where agency is assigned
	•	Who feels responsible
	•	What feels possible

Example:

“We need to improve performance.”
vs
“We need to eliminate friction.”
vs
“We need to unlock capacity.”

Each invokes different Levin-class causal schemas.

Different mental models.
Different downstream actions.

⸻

6️⃣ This Is Why You’re Right About Language Power

Language isn’t magic.

It’s a:
	•	Causal modeling tool
	•	Agency assignment tool
	•	Frame construction device
	•	Coordination protocol

When you change verbs,
you change perceived structure.

When you change structure,
you change decision-making.

That’s perlocutionary leverage.

⸻

7️⃣ The Discipline

The danger is believing:

Because language shapes modeling,
it directly shapes reality fields.

It doesn’t.

It shapes human behavior inside constraints.

That’s enough.

⸻

Let me ask you something specific:

Are you interested in mapping Pantheon concepts into precise verb classes to sharpen their operational clarity?

Because that would actually make it more universal.

And that would move you out of abstraction and into structural linguistics.

That’s a real lever.